Even though the normalisation of diplomatic channels between Israel and Morocco has stalled somewhat in 2021 with the resultant lack of ambassadors, embassies, or open liaison offices, there have been significant signs of some semblance of diplomatic recognition. King Mohammed VI, who is the highest authority in Morocco in both State and religious aspects, congratulated the new Prime Minister of Israel, Naftali Bennett on his election. Morocco’s main policy goal is to gain international recognition for its sovereignty over Western Sahara that was gained from Trump’s government as a prerequisite for normalising relations with Israel. The Israeli carrier Israir is commencing flights between Tel Aviv and Marrakesh in July 2021. Therefore, contrary to my previous argument, I will suggest (and concede) that Morocco is the sixth country to recognise Israel albeit sans consular facilities and given the overriding authority of the King.

Presently there are five Arab League states that have recognised the State of Israel which are Bahrain, Egypt, Jordan, Sudan and the UAE in some part to counter the threat that Iran represents. The sixth state expected to add to these was Oman. However, Oman prefers to remain a relationship with Iran that a recognition of Israel would harm. The recent conflict in Gaza and the condemnation from the Arab League of Israel concerning the plight of the Palestinians has halted any further recognition in the immediate future. Saudi foreign minister Prince Faisal bin Farhan stated that ‘the kingdom “categorically rejects the Israeli violations against Palestinians”, while calling for an immediate ceasefire’. The remote chance of Saudi Arabia recognising Israel as a bulwark to Iran is now more remote. A recent meeting of Muslim Nations concerning the Gaza conflict, criticized not only Israel but those Arab League countries who now recognised it.

The 2020 normalizations were somewhat transactional (unsure if this is the norm): Morocco, recognition of its sovereignty over Western Sahara; Bahrain, continued U.S. support; UAE, Israel suspended West Bank annexation plans in exchange for the U.S reversal of its position on the legality of settlements; Sudan was removed from the U.S. State Sponsor of Terrorism list.

For a member of the Arab League to recognize Israel as a state is a weighty political decision. Upon some research, a few Arab League members cited the treatment of Palestinians as a hesitation towards recognizing Israel as a state. As of May 2021, Israel could see new leadership (which could be more hospitable towards Palestinians), which may allow room for some countries to reconsider their current stance.

+10 to follow the crowd a little, and recent signs seem to show there could be at least a few more recognizing Israel in the coming months. Leaving a small percent on lower numbers in the event of some kind of conflict or breakdown of relations.

At present, 5 Arab League members (Bahrain, Egypt, Jordan, Sudan, and UAE) recognize Israel. There are reports of a recent meeting between Israel and SA (https://www.businessinsider.com/us-arranged-israel-saudi-meeting-as-reward-for-assassination-sources-2020-11), but that meeting was publicly denied by SA and no formal recognition resulted for now. Pundits believe that SA recognition is not possible under King Salman, but may be under his successor, MBS. The Trump administration made Arab recognition of Israel a key part of its foreign policy, but his failed reelection bid leaves the future of the recent momentum up in the air. I suspect many Arab states will wait to see how a new Biden administration approaches the subject. Still there is plenty of time before the question closes out, for at least one more Arab League member to recognize Israel.

The answer to this question depends on the reasons as to why the Arab League States would diplomatically recognise Israel after 70+ years of antagonism over the formation of the State and their support of Palestinians. Pragmatism has become a common thread that join certain Arab League Nations in their concern (fear) over the intentions and actions of Iran together with friendly relations with the U.S. together with Israel’s technological edge in fields when compared with the Arab League. Therefore, the number of member states most likely to recognise Israel by 28 August 2021 would be probably 4.

Algeria, Bahrain, Comoros, Djibouti, Egypt, Iraq, Jordan, Kuwait, Lebanon, Libya, Mauritania, Morocco, Oman, Palestine, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, Somalia, Sudan, Syria, Tunisia, the United Arab Emirates, and Yemen.
